   <title>Recommendations for Formal Assessment</title>
   <sect2 id="ch0014s0003s01" role="Heading">
      <title>Tools for the Formal Assessment of SSRD in Adults</title>
      <sect3 id="ch0014s0003s01s01" role="Heading">
         <title>Clinical Interviews</title>
         <para role="Para">The <emphasis>Diagnostic Interview for Anxiety, Mood, and OCD and Related Neuropsychiatric Disorders</emphasis> (<emphasis>DIAMOND</emphasis>) is one<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>one</primary>
            </indexterm> of the best validated structured interviews (Tolin et al., <emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>2018</phrase>
            </emphasis>) to assess current (not lifespan) SSD and IAD. In addition to determining whether an individual meets the diagnostic criteria, clinicians have the opportunity to rate the severity of the disorder on a scale from 1 (normal) to 7 (extreme) based on their clinical judgment of the patient’s current level of distress. Interrater and test-retest reliability across all diagnoses were rated very good to excellent, and evidence for convergent validity was established for almost all diagnoses (Tolin et al., <emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>2018</phrase>
            </emphasis>). The DIAMOND<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>DIAMOND</primary>
            </indexterm> is accessible for free.</para>
         <para role="Para">The <emphasis>Structured Clinical Interview for DSM-5 Disorders</emphasis> (<emphasis>SCID-5</emphasis>) is a semi-structured interview and exists in different versions. The clinical version (SCID-5-CV) only screens for SSD and IAD (First et al., <emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>2016</phrase>
            </emphasis>). The most<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>most</primary>
            </indexterm> comprehensive version of the SCID-5 is the research version, SCID-5-RV (First et al., <emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>2015</phrase>
            </emphasis>), which includes a section on current SSD and IAD. Similar to the DIAMOND<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>DIAMOND</primary>
            </indexterm>, the questions of the SCID-5 operationalize the diagnostic criteria of the disorder in DSM-5. The clinician has to choose between whether a symptom is absent/subthreshold or the threshold is met. So far, psychometric data are provided for the clinical version of the SCID-5 regarding validity, sensitivity and specificity, interrater reliability, as well as test-retest reliability (Osorio et al., <emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>2019</phrase>
            </emphasis>).</para>
         <para role="Para">Another semi-structured interview that was specifically designed to evaluate emotional and related disorders and claims to be more circumscribed compared to the SCID and DIAMOND is the <emphasis>Anxiety and Related Disorders Interview Schedule for DSM-5</emphasis> (<emphasis>ADIS-5</emphasis>) by Brown and Barlow (<emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>2014</phrase>
            </emphasis>). The ADIS-5 allows differential diagnoses between all anxiety and related disorders and includes a section on current as well as lifetime SSD and IAD. The clinician provides a clinical severity rating on a 9-point severity scale to distinguish between clinical and<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>and</primary>
            </indexterm>subclinical diagnoses. The lifetime version of the ADIS-5 (ADIS-5L) is designed to capture past (lifetime) diagnoses. So far, psychometric data has not been available for the ADIS-5, but just for its predecessor, the ADIS-IV. unstructured clinical interviews<link linkend="ch0014s0001fg01">12.1</link>
            <link linkend="ch0014s0001fg02">12.2</link>
            <phrase>12.1</phrase>Table 12.1</para>
         medical<indexterm significance="normal">
            <primary>medical</primary>
         </indexterm>
         <para role="SimplePara">Topics that should<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>should</primary>
            </indexterm> be addressed in an unstructured interview for SSRD</para>
         <table id="ch0014s0003ta01">
            <title/>
            <tgroup cols="1">
               <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1"/>
               <tbody>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">Reason for seeking psychotherapy:</emphasis> Did you get referred? If yes, why? Why did you decide to seek psychotherapy right now?</para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">Exploration of the somatic symptoms and of the impact of symptoms on and interference with patient’s life:</emphasis> Family/partnership? Job? Social life? Other areas?</para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">How does your social environment react to and deal with your symptoms?:</emphasis> Family/partner? Workplace? Friends? Health care? Other areas?</para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">What have you done so far to cope with your somatic symptoms?:</emphasis> Which medical/pharmacological treatments? How successful? Do you take medication because of your symptoms? If yes, which ones? How often and which dosage?</para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">Do you have any medical conditions or problems with your mental health? If yes, which ones?</emphasis>
                        </para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">I am sure you have already thought a lot about your symptoms. Do you have any ideas of how your symptoms could be explained or what has caused them?</emphasis>
                        </para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">Personal history/biography and how is your life currently?:</emphasis> Partnership? Family? Job/training? Financial situation? Social network? Resources and positive activities? Other areas? Stressful life events during the past year that could be related to the onset of your symptoms?</para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">What are your hopes and expectations about seeking help from a psychologist?:</emphasis> What do you think how psychotherapy could help you?</para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                     <entry>
                        <para role="SimplePara">
                           <emphasis role="strong">Are you ok with me contacting your primary care provider (or other medical specialists and healthcare providers who are involved in the treatment of the patient’s symptoms?):</emphasis> Gain patients’ consent to contact other healthcare provider(s)</para>
                     </entry>
                  </row>
               </tbody>
            </tgroup>
         </table>
      </sect3>
