      <sect3 id="ch0014s0003s01s04" role="Heading">
         <title>Tools to Document Informants’ Observations</title>
         <para role="Para">There are not many tools available that help with documenting the informants’ observations. Vlaeyen et al. (<emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>1990</phrase>
            </emphasis>) developed the Checklist for Interpersonal Pain Behavior (CHIP)<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>Checklist for Interpersonal Pain Behavior (CHIP)</primary>
            </indexterm> specifically for patients with pain symptoms, which covers six domains of problematic symptom-related behaviors: distorted mobility, verbal complaints, nonverbal complaints, nervousness, depression, and<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>and</primary>
            </indexterm> day sleeping. Scales like the CHIP can be easily adjusted to other somatic symptoms.</para>
      </sect3>
      <sect3 id="ch0014s0003s01s05" role="Heading">
         <title>Behavioral Observation Tools</title>
         <para role="Para">Avoidance behavior (e. g., avoiding certain movements because of the fear of inducing pain) is a very common illness behavior across different types of SSRD that needs special attention in the diagnostic process because it can turn into a subtle yet highly automated behavior. Observational methods can help clinicians to identify and characterize avoidance behavior. The Photograph Series of Daily Activities (PHODA)<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>Photograph Series of Daily Activities (PHODA)</primary>
            </indexterm> is a popular tool to observe pain-related avoidance<indexterm significance="normal">
               <primary>avoidance</primary>
            </indexterm> behaviors (Oliveira et al., <emphasis role="CitationRef">
               <phrase>2018</phrase>
            </emphasis>).</para>
      </sect3>
   </sect2>
   <sect2 id="ch0014s0003s02" role="Heading">
      <title>Tools for the Formal Assessment of SSRD in Children and Adolescents</title>
      <para role="Para">
         Formal assessment<indexterm significance="normal">
            <primary>Formal assessment</primary>
         </indexterm>tools to support the diagnosis of an SSRD in children and adolescents are very limited and were mostly developed to assess pain. According to the PedIMMPACT (Mc Grath et al.,<emphasis role="CitationRef">
            <phrase>2008</phrase>
         </emphasis>) recommendations, traditional self-report tools to rate pain intensity can be used for children who are 8 years of age or older. Unidimensional measures such as visual analogue scales, numerical rating scales, or verbal rating scales (Lalloo &amp; Stinson, <emphasis role="CitationRef">
            <phrase>2014</phrase>
         </emphasis>) are available. For children who are in pre-school age (5–7 years), graphic rating scales, e. g., Pieces of Hurt Tool (Hester,<emphasis role="CitationRef">
            <phrase>1979</phrase>
         </emphasis>), should be applied. Observational/behavioral scales are suggested for children who are 5 years of age or younger. There are several scales validated for children who are aged between 0 and 5 years, e. g., COMFORTneo (van Dijk et al.,<emphasis role="CitationRef">
            <phrase>2009</phrase>
         </emphasis>). Besides pain intensity, children and their caregivers’ perspectives on the pain-related<indexterm significance="normal">
            <primary>pain-related</primary>
         </indexterm>disability (e. g., Bath Adolescent Pain Questionnaire for adolescents aged between 13 and 18 years; Eccleston et al.,<emphasis role="CitationRef">
            <phrase>2005</phrase>
         </emphasis>) and health-related quality of life (e. g., Paediatric Quality of Life; Varni et al.,<emphasis role="CitationRef">
            <phrase>1999</phrase>
         </emphasis>) should be considered.</para>
   </sect2>
</sect1>